post_text:
Did you know September is National Childhood Obesity Awareness Month? Our Nurses have some facts for you:
September is National Childhood Obesity Awareness Month. According to the CDC, about 1 in 5 children in the United States have obesity. This is a national health concern as children with obesity are at a higher risk of chronic health conditions such as type 2 diabetes, asthma, sleep apnea, heart disease, and bone and joint problems.
There are many ways educators and families can help adolescents maintain a healthy weight by helping to develop healthier eating habits, encouraging regular physical activity, and promoting healthy behaviors such as reduced screen time and adequate sleep.

post_text:
Did you know July 24 is National Amelia Earhart Day?! Check out 21CCCS Social Studies teacher Ms. Elder's thoughts on this motivational historical figure:

"By the time of Amelia Earhart's disappearance in 1937, women had only been allowed to vote for 17 years. She broke barriers for women by braving the new world of flight, becoming the first woman to cross the Atlantic in an airplane. At that time, flying wasn't considered "ladylike", but she helped show the world that women can do anything if they put their minds to it.

She spent much of her career working to help promote women's opportunities in aviation and in other fields, believing that women should help to open doors for other women. Her life may have been cut short, but in her 39 years, she made a great impact on the world!"

Today we celebrate #NationalHydrationDay by reminding you of the importance of proper hydration. As summer heats up and your time outside increases, it’s even more important to replace the fluids that your body loses through sweating to promote optimal physical health and avoid symptoms of dehydration like lethargy, headaches, and more.

If you’re someone who doesn’t love drinking water, add a little zing by adding mint leaves, a squeeze of lemon or lime, or some cucumber slices. Stay active, stay healthy, and have fun! #21CCCS #21Cyberstrong

This year, #21CCCS Radio Theatre Club is comprised of over 15 students who are passionate about the arts. RTC members are writers, artists, actors and actresses, singers, musicians, editors and directors. They spend the start of the year playing games, performing skits, sharing art, enjoying mini lessons and getting to know each other. The remainder of the year is spent creating a production.

This year's production is their arrangement of Tangled, led by Ms. Kemmerer and student-directed by Alethia F., who has dedicated so much of her time to the show. Congratulations to everyone involved – we’re so impressed with your talents and creativity! Enjoy the performance in full, here: https://wi.st/2AdeiJy. #21CyberStrong

post_text:
For #NationalSpaceDay we reached out to Maria Alexis, an incredible Science teacher here at #21CCCS, to find out more about her experience at NASA. From 2010 - 2016, Maria spent time at NASA each summer collaborating with other teachers to create STEM Units, lessons and assessments for NASA.

This led to a 3 year opportunity to coordinate a local NASA Summer of Innovation Camp in Chester County, which invited students to experience NASA STEM activities, learn about engineering, rocketry, aeronautics, robotics, the Sun and our solar system, earth science and weather.

Watch to learn more about her experience, how it helped her teach science to students, and some surprising facts she learned along the way! #21CyberStrong #NASA #SpaceDay

Today, we’d like to recognize a student who not only excels in our rigorous program at #21CCCS, but also in her career as a dancer. Emma M. has been awarded multiple scholarships to attend DeSales University, where she plans to major in Dance. Emma has been practicing for 15 years and says she enjoys “the constant challenge. I just really love dance and can't see my life without it.”

DeSales offers master classes with professionals from the field of dance and has had a dance program for 35 years, which encouraged Emma’s decision to attend the university. One of the scholarships Emma received is called the “Raising the Barre Scholarship,” which comes from a youth service non-profit organization aimed at bettering communities through dance.

Congratulations Emma! We can’t wait to watch you thrive at DeSales! #21CCCS #21CyberStrong #StudentSpotlight

We would like to give a shout out to #21CCCS alum, Natalie W, who was recently featured in the Reading Eagle!

Natalie is a skilled gymnast who leveraged her talents into a gymnastics career at the University of Michigan, where she was an NCAA champ on the balance beam, All-American in the all-around and scored the school’s first perfect 10 on the vault in eight years during her freshman year.

Natalie was set to compete in the NCAA Championships at Fort Worth for gymnastics this year, which was unfortunately canceled.

While her plans may be on hold, we are still so unbelievably proud of this 21CCCS alum. We know you’ll keep up your hard work and continue to look ahead to the future! Read more about Natalie, here: https://bit.ly/3aipfFY

Congratulations to our #StudentSpotlight, Rachel P, for being accepted into the honors program at Messiah College, where she will be majoring in history and minoring in music.

Rachel is a musician and has been playing piano for over 10 years and trombone for over 7 years, which lead her to participate in the Cumberland County Band Festival for 6 years and successfully audition for the PMEA District 7 Upper Band festival for 2 years. This year, Rachel will also be playing in the District 7 Jazz Festival.

Great job, Rachel! #21CyberStrong

post_text: There is no one more dedicated to the students, staff, vision and mission of 21CCCS than Lauren Michener. When a student or staff member brings an issue to Lauren, one thing happens: the issue gets solved and she usually has a large hand in making it happen. To label Lauren as just a problem solver brushes aside the fact that she is a leader, creative force, devoted educator, and thorough planner. These traits were essential in Lauren leading the charge for 21CCCS being recognized as an Apple Distinguished School. Anna Sewell wrote in her infamous 1877 novel Black Beauty, "It is good people who make good places." Lauren is good people. She inspires and guides others to make this school a good place with her selfless actions and tireless positive attitude. #21CCCS #21Cyberstrong #IWD2020

post_text:
Recently, our middle school students visited The Lancaster Science Factory where they learned about the world of physics and worked in teams to create a lie detector, launch a helicopter and so much more.

Students also had the opportunity to explore exhibits on fluid dynamics, mechanics, motion, acoustics and sound, math and logic, structural engineering, light and vision and electricity and magnetism, to name a few. Some favorites included the Rock and Roll Sound Stage, the Energy Floor and the Test Flight Zone. Thanks for all who joined us! #21CyberStrong #21CCCS

Today, we’re recognizing #21CCCS student Nay'yarrah in honor of National Girls and Women in Sports Day.

In 2018, Nay'yarrah was diagnosed with Graves’ Disease, but she has not let it affect her gymnastics and has already been accepted into 4 colleges. Her hard work has led her to become a declared specialist on the gymnastics vault and floor. In 2020 Nay'yarrah has already placed first on floor at her first meet of the season! #21CyberStrong

When it comes to college, every penny counts. Fortunately, you can use your student ID to unlock savings - just ask about special offers for students at places you shop!

It may not seem like much at the time, but even if only half your purchases are 15% off, yearly savings can amount to thousands!

Check out some student-friendly stores here: https://bit.ly/2t37lnz and tune in every #TipTuesday for more ways to save. #21CCCS #21Cyberstrong

post_text:
Are you wondering how to stay financially fit in college? Consider participating in your college’s work-study program! If you want to cut down on your cost of living at the same time, you can become a Resident Advisor (RA). Many schools will pay RA’s and contribute to their room and board. If you are too busy to work during the school year, take up a summer job to help you pay for tuition, books or other college expenses.

Make sure to follow us every #TipTuesday for tips on how to not break the bank in college! #21CCCS #CyberStrong

How can you save on costs in college? One way is to buy used textbooks, which can be found online or in your school’s bookstore. You can also rent textbooks, and some books are even available as digital versions for your computer, phone or tablet.

Bonus: If you do purchase textbooks (used or new) you can sell them for a little extra cash once you’re done with them! #TipTuesday #21CCCS #21CyberStrong

post_text:
Meet this week’s #StudentSpotlight, Sasha H!

Sasha is the 2019 recipient of the St. Lawrence University Book Award, which recognizes a member of the junior class who has consistently demonstrated academic success while establishing themselves as an integral and committed member of her community. In addition to this year's selected book, The Last Lecture by Randy Pausch, Sasha will also receive a yearly merit scholarship if she applies and is accepted to St. Lawrence University.

GREAT work Sasha! #21CCCS #21CyberStrong

post_text: Check out this awesome production by our Radio and Theatre Club! All year, the club held classes and practices that ultimately culminated in this performance of Agatha Christie and the Case of the Careless Victim. post_text:
Students, parents, and teachers gathered to participate in a nationwide Holocaust remembrance effort called The Butterfly Project. The butterflies were painted beautifully and will be on permanent display at our Murrysville location.

A special thank you goes out to Alyssa J. for initiating the Butterfly project, and to all of the students who participated. Alyssa said, “The butterfly project is very special to me as my grandparents were survivors of the Holocaust. This project was a way to lead and teach students about the Holocaust in a fun, nonthreatening way and to cultivate empathy and social change against intolerance.” #21CCCS #21CyberStrong #TheButterflyProject #HolocaustRemembrance

post_text: Our screens, particularly social media, can provide amazing opportunities and resources that didn’t exist just 5, 10, 20 years ago. While there are so many great things about having access to the internet, it’s also important to regulate screen time. Join us for our March Awareness Assembly to discuss Screen Time Addiction; What is it? What are the symptoms? What can you do to manage it? Join us to find out! #21CCCS #CyberStrong

post_text: We recently hosted the Pennsylvania School Counselor Symposium, an event that brought together PA Cyber School Counselors from all across the Commonwealth to participate in professional development. Topics included Career and College Readiness, Student Assistance Program, Virtual Counseling, Student Engagement, Best Practices in Cyber School Counseling and Trauma Centered Care. Thank you to PA Distance Learning Charter School for organizing the event, and to Mr. Sean Galiczynski for presenting! #21CCCS #21CyberStrong

post_text:
Our #StudentSpotlight, Michelle J. (wearing blue, standing next to the Mayor and Councilman Corey O’Connor) and her group meet bi-monthly in the PPS office to develop skills and do research as a solidified participatory action team for Pittsburgh city issues.

They typically discuss Pittsburgh priorities such as gentrification of neighborhoods, allocation of resources, road conditions and school funding. Last Monday, they met with Mayor Peduto and Councilman Corey O’Connor to discuss leadership skills and their budget project development, as well as gun violence.

We’re so proud of our hard-working students and future leaders! Keep up the great work, Michelle J. #21CCCS #21CyberStrong

post_text:
Today we shine our Student Spotlight on Jack and Vern, who started Tae-Kwon-Do at 6 years old. They compete in regional tournaments 4 times per year and train at West Chester ATA.

Jack received first place in Extreme Weapons with the sword, first place in Combat Sparring, and third place in Weapons. He will test for his Second Degree Black Belt in March 2019.

Vern received second place in Extreme Weapons, Sparring, Forms, Weapons, and Combat Sparring. Vern also tested for his Second Degree Black Belt, which has taken him 3 years.

Way to go, Jack and Vern! #21CCCS #21CyberStrong
